* Prioritizing GET and POST in PHP

* GET Method
    * Appends data to the URL.
    * Used for retrieving data.
    * Can be bookmarked, shared, and cached.
    * Not secure for sensitive data (visible in URL).
    * Limit on the amount of data (URL length limit).

* Use GET When:
    * You're just retrieving data.
    * You want users to bookmark or share the URL.
    * Example: Searching for products, filtering data.

* POST Method
    * Sends data in the HTTP request body (not visible in URL).
    * Used for submitting data securely.
    * No size limit for data (practically).
    * Cannot be bookmarked or cached.

* Use POST When:
    * You're submitting forms with sensitive information.
    * You're updating or inserting data (e.g., login, registration).


Using POST:

<?php
if ($_SERVER["REQUEST_METHOD"] == "POST") {
    $name = htmlspecialchars($_POST["name"]);
    $email = htmlspecialchars($_POST["email"]);
    echo "Hello, $name. We will contact you at $email.";
}
?>

<form method="post" action="">
    Name: <input type="text" name="name"><br><br>
    Email: <input type="email" name="email"><br><br>
    <input type="submit" value="Submit">
</form>


Using GET:

<?php
if (isset($_GET['query'])) {
    $query = htmlspecialchars($_GET['query']);
    echo "You searched for: $query";
}
?>

<form method="get" action="">
    Search: <input type="text" name="query">
    <input type="submit" value="Search">
</form>

